00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:18.000
Speaking of history, let's jump in. There's a possibility that people out there listening don't know what Pandas is.

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:26.000
You would think it's pretty ubiquitous, and I certainly would say that it is, especially in the data science space,

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:32.000
but I've got a bunch of listeners who listen, and they say really surprising things.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:36.000
They'll say stuff to me like, Michael, I've been listening for six weeks now,

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:39.000
and I'm starting to understand some of the stuff you all are talking about.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:44.000
Why did you listen for six weeks? You didn't know what I was talking about. That's crazy.

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:48.000
A lot of people use it as language immersion to get into the Python space.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:53.000
I'm sure there's plenty of people out there who are immersing themselves but are pretty new.

00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:57.000
Maybe for that crew, we could introduce what Pandas is.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:05.000
Absolutely. It's a data manipulation and analysis toolkit for Python.

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:10.000
It's a Python library that you install that enables you to read data files,

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:15.000
so read many different types of data files off of disk or off of remote storage

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:20.000
or read data out of a database or some other remote data storage system.

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:24.000
This is tabular data, so it's structured data like with columns.

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:28.000
You can think of it like a spreadsheet or some other tabular data set.

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:37.000
Then it provides you with this DataFrame object, which is Pandas.DataFrame,

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:40.000
that is the main tabular data object.

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:47.000
It has a ton of methods for accessing, slicing, grabbing subsets of the data,

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:52.000
applying functions on it that do filtering and subsetting and selection

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:58.000
as well as more analytical operations like things that you might do with a database system or SQL,

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:04.000
so joins and lookups as well as analytical functions like summary statistics,

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:09.000
grouping by some key and producing summary statistics.

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:15.000
It's basically a Swiss army knife for doing data manipulation, data cleaning,

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:18.000
and supporting the data analysis workflow.

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:23.000
But it doesn't actually include very much as far as actual statistics or models

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:28.000
or if you're doing something with LLMs or linear regression

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:32.000
or some type of machine learning, you have to use another library,

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:39.000
but Pandas is the on-ramp for all of the data into your environment in Python.

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:44.000
So when people are building some kind of application that touches data in Python,

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:50.000
Pandas is often the initial on-ramp for how data gets into Python

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:55.000
where you clean up the data, you regularize it, you get it ready for analysis,

00:10:55.000 --> 00:11:02.000
and then you feed the clean data into the downstream statistical library

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:05.000
or data analysis library that you're using.

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:08.000
That whole data wrangling side of things, right?

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:11.000
Yeah, that's right.

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:15.000
And so it's some history.

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:22.000
So Python had arrays like matrices and what we call tensors now,

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:26.000
multidimensional arrays going back all the way to 1995,

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:31.000
which is pretty early history for Python.

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:36.000
The Python programming language has only been around since 1990 or 1991,

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:38.000
if my memory serves.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:45.000
But what became NumPy in 2005-2006 started out as numeric in 1995,

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:50.000
and it provided numerical computing, multidimensional arrays, matrices,

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:52.000
the kind of stuff that you might do in MATLAB,

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:55.000
but it was mainly focused on numerical computing

00:11:55.000 --> 00:12:00.000
and not with the type of business data sets that you find in database systems

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:05.000
which contain a lot of strings or dates or non-numeric data.

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:09.000
And so my initial interest was I found Python

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:11.000
to be a really productive programming language.

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:13.000
I really liked writing code in it, writing simple scripts,

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:17.000
like doing random things for my job.

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:21.000
And you had this numerical computing library, NumPy,

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:24.000
which enabled you to work with large numeric arrays

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:28.000
and large data sets with a single data type.

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:30.000
But working with this more tabular type data,

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:33.000
stuff that you would do in Excel or stuff that you do in a database,

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:36.000
it wasn't very easy to do that with NumPy,

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:38.000
or it wasn't really designed for that.

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:42.000
And so that's what led to building this higher-level library

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:46.000
that deals with these tabular data sets in the Pandas library,

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:49.000
which was originally focused on building

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:52.000
with a really close relationship with NumPy.

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:57.000
So Pandas itself was like a thin layer on top of NumPy originally.

00:12:57.000 --> 00:12:59.000
One thing I find interesting about Pandas

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:04.000
is it's almost its own programming environment these days

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:08.000
in the sense that traditional Python,

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:10.000
we do a lot of loops.

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:16.000
We do a lot of attribute dereferencing, function calling.

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:20.000
And a lot of what happens in Pandas is more functional.

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:23.000
It's more applied to us.

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:26.000
It's almost like set operations, right?

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:29.000
And a lot of vector operations and so on.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:35.000
Yeah, and that was behaviors inherited from NumPy.

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:39.000
So NumPy is very array-oriented, vector-oriented.

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:45.000
So rather than write a for loop, you would write an array expression

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:48.000
which would operate on whole batches of data

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:51.000
in a single function call,

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:55.000
which is a lot faster because you can drop down into C code

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:57.000
and get good performance that way.

00:13:57.000 --> 00:14:04.000
And so Pandas adopted the NumPy way of the NumPy-like array expression

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:07.000
or vector operations.

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:13.000
But it's true that that's extended to the types of non-numeric data operations

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:17.000
that you can do in Pandas, like vectorized set lookups

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:19.000
where you can say, like, you would say, like,

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:23.000
oh, I have this array of strings and I have this subset of strings

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:27.000
and I want to compute a Boolean array which says whether or not

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:30.000
each string is contained in this set of strings.

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:33.000
And so in Pandas, that's the is-in function.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:37.000
So you would say, like, you know, column A, like, is in

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:39.000
some set of substrings and that produces,

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:42.000
that single function call produces a whole Boolean array

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:46.000
that you can use for subsetting later on.

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:51.000
Yeah, there's a ton of things that are really interesting in there.

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:54.000
One of the challenges, maybe you could speak to this a little bit,

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:57.000
then I want to come back to your performance comment.

