00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:17.000
If you look at Pandoc, if people haven't looked at this before,

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:22.000
the conversion matrix, I don't know how you would…

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:24.000
How would you describe this, Wes?

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:25.000
Busy?

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:26.000
Complete?

00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:27.000
What is this?

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:28.000
This is crazy.

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:29.000
It's very busy, yeah.

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:36.000
It looks like about 30 or 40 input formats to 50 or 60 output formats,

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:38.000
maybe more than that.

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:39.000
Am I just eyeballing it?

00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:43.000
But, yeah, it's pretty impressive.

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:46.000
And then if you took the combinatorial of, like,

00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:49.000
how many different ways could you combine the 30 to the 50,

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:50.000
it's kind of what it looks like.

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:52.000
It's truly amazing.

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:55.000
So if you've got Markdown, you want to turn it into a PDF,

00:19:55.000 --> 00:20:00.000
or you've got a Doku wiki and you want to turn it into an EPUB or whatever,

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:05.000
or even, like, RevealJS probably to PowerPoint, I would imagine.

00:20:05.000 --> 00:20:06.000
I don't know.

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:11.000
Well, as history, like, back story about Quarto,

00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:15.000
so it helps to keep in mind that JJ created ColdFusion,

00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:19.000
which was this, you know, essentially publishing system,

00:20:19.000 --> 00:20:23.000
early publishing system for the internet,

00:20:23.000 --> 00:20:29.000
similar to CGI and PHP and other dynamic, you know, web publishing systems.

00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:34.000
And so early on at RStudio, they created RMarkdown,

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:42.000
which is basically extensions to Markdown that allow you to have code cells

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:46.000
written in R, and then eventually they added support for some other languages

00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:49.000
where it's kind of like a Jupyter Notebook in the sense that you could have

00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:52.000
some Markdown and some code and some plots and output,

00:20:52.000 --> 00:20:56.000
and you would run the RMarkdown renderer and it would, you know,

00:20:56.000 --> 00:21:00.000
generate all the output and insert it into the document.

00:21:00.000 --> 00:21:04.000
And so you could use that to write blogs and websites and everything.

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:09.000
But RMarkdown was written in R, and so that limited, in a sense,

00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:14.000
like it made it harder to install because you would have to install R to use it.

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:18.000
And also people, you know, it had an association with R

00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:20.000
that perhaps was, like, unmerited.

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:24.000
And so in the meantime, you know, with everything that's happened

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:31.000
with web technology, it's now very easy to put a complete JavaScript engine

00:21:31.000 --> 00:21:36.000
in a small install footprint, you know, on a machine with no dependencies

00:21:36.000 --> 00:21:43.000
and to be able to run a system that is, you know, written in a system

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:44.000
that's written in JavaScript.

00:21:44.000 --> 00:21:46.000
And so Cordo is completely language agnostic.

00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:51.000
It's written in TypeScript, and it uses Pandoc as an underlying engine,

00:21:51.000 --> 00:21:53.000
and it's very easy to install.

00:21:53.000 --> 00:21:59.000
And so it addresses some of the portability and, you know,

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:03.000
extents that were in RMarkdown.

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:07.000
But as a result, you know, I think the Posit team had a lot of,

00:22:07.000 --> 00:22:11.000
just has more than, you know, a decade, or if you include ColdFusion,

00:22:11.000 --> 00:22:15.000
you know, more than 25 years of experience in building

00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:18.000
really developer-friendly technical publishing tools.

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:22.000
And so I think that it's not data science,

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:26.000
but it's something that is an important part of the data science workflow,

00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:30.000
which is how do you present your, make your analysis and your work

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:32.000
available for consumption in different forms.

00:22:32.000 --> 00:22:37.000
And so having this system that can, you know, publish outputs

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:42.000
in many different places is super valuable.

00:22:42.000 --> 00:22:46.000
So a lot of people start out in Jupyter Notebooks, but, you know,

00:22:46.000 --> 00:22:49.000
but there's many different, you know, many different possible input formats.

00:22:49.000 --> 00:22:52.000
And so to be able to, you know, use the same source to publish to a website

00:22:52.000 --> 00:22:57.000
or to a confluence page or to a PDF is like super valuable.

00:22:57.000 --> 00:22:59.000
Yeah, it's super interesting.

00:22:59.000 --> 00:23:00.000
Okay.

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:02.000
So then I got to explore some more.

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:05.000
Let's go back to Pandas for a minute.

00:23:05.000 --> 00:23:08.000
First, how about some kind words from the audience for you?

00:23:08.000 --> 00:23:11.000
Ravid says, Wes, your work has changed my life.

00:23:11.000 --> 00:23:15.000
It's very, very nice.

00:23:15.000 --> 00:23:17.000
I'm happy to hear it.

00:23:17.000 --> 00:23:23.000
But yeah, I'm more than happy to, yeah, talk in depth about Pandas.

00:23:23.000 --> 00:23:26.000
And I think the history of the project is interesting.

00:23:26.000 --> 00:23:32.000
And I think also how the project has developed in the intervening 15,

00:23:32.000 --> 00:23:35.000
16 years is pretty interesting as well.

00:23:35.000 --> 00:23:36.000
Yeah.

00:23:36.000 --> 00:23:39.000
Let's talk derivatives for a minute.

00:23:39.000 --> 00:23:45.000
So growth and speed of adoption and all those things.

00:23:45.000 --> 00:23:48.000
When you first started working on this and you first put it out,

00:23:48.000 --> 00:23:54.000
did you foresee a world where this was so popular and so important?

00:23:54.000 --> 00:23:57.000
Did you think of, yeah, pretty soon black holes.

00:23:57.000 --> 00:24:00.000
I'm pretty sure I'll be part of that somehow.

00:24:00.000 --> 00:24:06.000
I mean, it was always the aspiration.

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:17.000
There was the aspiration there of making Python this mainstream language

00:24:17.000 --> 00:24:21.000
for statistical computing and data analysis.

00:24:21.000 --> 00:24:28.000
I didn't – it didn't occur to me that it would become this popular

00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:33.000
or that it would become one of the main tools that people use for working

00:24:33.000 --> 00:24:36.000
with data in a business setting.

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:41.000
It would have been – if that was the aspiration or if that was what I needed

00:24:41.000 --> 00:24:46.000
to achieve to be satisfied, that would have been completely unreasonable.

00:24:46.000 --> 00:24:50.000
And I also don't think that – in a certain sense,

00:24:50.000 --> 00:24:56.000
I don't know that its popularity – it is deserved and it's deserved.

00:24:56.000 --> 00:25:00.000
I think there's many other worthy efforts that have been created over the years

00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:08.000
that have been really great work that others have done in this domain.

00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:14.000
And so the fact that Pandas caught on and became as popular as it is,

00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:19.000
I think it's a combination of timing and there was a developer relations aspect

00:25:19.000 --> 00:25:22.000
that there was content available, and I wrote my book,

00:25:22.000 --> 00:25:25.000
and that made it easier for people to learn how to use the project.

00:25:25.000 --> 00:25:30.000
But also we had a serendipitous open-source developer community

00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:37.000
that came together that led the project to grow and expand really rapidly

00:25:37.000 --> 00:25:40.000
in the early 2010s.

00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:46.000
And I definitely spent a lot of work recruiting people to work on the project

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:50.000
and encouraging others to work on it because sometimes people create

00:25:50.000 --> 00:25:53.000
open-source projects and then it's hard for others to get involved

00:25:53.000 --> 00:25:56.000
and get a seat at the table, so to speak.

00:25:56.000 --> 00:26:02.000
But I was very keen to bring on others and to give them responsibility

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:08.000
and ultimately hand over the reins to the project to others.

00:26:08.000 --> 00:26:13.000
And I've spoken a lot about that over the years, how important that is

00:26:13.000 --> 00:26:19.000
for open-source project creators to make room for others in growing the project

00:26:19.000 --> 00:26:24.000
so that they can become owners of it as well.

00:26:24.000 --> 00:26:29.000
It's tough to make space and tough to bring on folks.

00:26:29.000 --> 00:26:33.000
Have you heard of the Djangonauts?

00:26:33.000 --> 00:26:35.000
I think it's djangonauts.space.

00:26:35.000 --> 00:26:37.000
They have an awesome domain.

00:26:37.000 --> 00:26:41.000
But it's basically kind of like a boot camp, but it's for taking people

00:26:41.000 --> 00:26:44.000
who just like Django and turning them into actually contributors

00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:46.000
or core contributors.

00:26:47.000 --> 00:26:52.000
What's your onboarding story for people who do want to participate?

00:26:52.000 --> 00:26:59.000
I'm embarrassed to say that I don't have a comprehensive view of all

00:26:59.000 --> 00:27:04.000
of the different community outreach channels that the Pandas project

00:27:04.000 --> 00:27:07.000
has done to help grow new contributors.

00:27:07.000 --> 00:27:14.000
So one of the core team members, Mark Garcia, has done an amazing job

00:27:14.000 --> 00:27:22.000
organizing documentation sprints and other contributor sourcing events,

00:27:22.000 --> 00:27:27.000
essentially creating very friendly accessible events where people

00:27:27.000 --> 00:27:30.000
who are interested in getting involved in Pandas can meet each other

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:34.000
and then assist each other in making their first pull request.

00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:38.000
And it could be something as simple as making a small improvement

00:27:38.000 --> 00:27:41.000
to the Pandas documentation because it's such a large project.

00:27:41.000 --> 00:27:47.000
The documentation is always something that could be made better,

00:27:47.000 --> 00:27:51.000
either adding more examples or documenting things that aren't documented

00:27:51.000 --> 00:27:55.000
or just making the documentation better.

00:27:55.000 --> 00:27:59.000
And so it's something that for new contributors is more accessible

00:27:59.000 --> 00:28:04.000
than working on the internals of one of the algorithms or something.

00:28:04.000 --> 00:28:08.000
Or working on some significant performance improvement

00:28:08.000 --> 00:28:10.000
might be a bit intimidating.

00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:13.000
If you've never worked on the Pandas code base, it's a pretty large code base

00:28:13.000 --> 00:28:18.000
because it's been worked on continuously for going on 20 years.

00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:24.000
So it takes a while to really get to a place where you can be productive,

00:28:24.000 --> 00:28:26.000
and that can be discouraging for new contributors,

00:28:26.000 --> 00:28:31.000
especially those who don't have a lot of open source experience.

00:28:31.000 --> 00:28:35.000
That's one of the ironies or challenges of these big projects

00:28:35.000 --> 00:28:38.000
is they're just so finely polished.

00:28:38.000 --> 00:28:40.000
So many people are using them.

00:28:40.000 --> 00:28:43.000
Every edge case matters to somebody, right?

00:28:43.000 --> 00:28:46.000
And so to become a contributor and make changes to that,

00:28:46.000 --> 00:28:48.000
it takes a while, I'm sure.

00:28:48.000 --> 00:28:49.000
Yeah.

00:28:49.000 --> 00:28:56.000
I mean, I think it's definitely a big thing that helped is allowing people

00:28:56.000 --> 00:29:02.000
to get paid to work on Pandas or to be able to contribute to Pandas

00:29:02.000 --> 00:29:05.000
as part of their job description,

00:29:05.000 --> 00:29:09.000
as maybe part of their job is maintaining Pandas.

00:29:09.000 --> 00:29:17.000
So Anaconda was one of the earliest companies who had engineers on staff,

00:29:17.000 --> 00:29:23.000
like Brock Mendel, Tom Augsberger, Jeff Reback,

00:29:23.000 --> 00:29:27.000
who part of their job was maintaining and developing Pandas.

00:29:27.000 --> 00:29:32.000
And that was huge because prior to that, the project was purely based on volunteers.

00:29:32.000 --> 00:29:36.000
Like I was a volunteer and everyone was working on the project

00:29:36.000 --> 00:29:40.000
as a passion project in their free time.

00:29:40.000 --> 00:29:44.000
And then Travis Oliphant, one of the founders,

00:29:44.000 --> 00:29:47.000
he and Peter Wang founded Anaconda.

00:29:47.000 --> 00:29:49.000
Travis went out from Anaconda to create Quonsight

00:29:49.000 --> 00:29:55.000
and has continued to sponsor development in and around Pandas.

00:29:55.000 --> 00:30:01.000
And that's enabled people like Mark to do these community-building events

00:30:01.000 --> 00:30:08.000
and for it to not be something that's totally uncompensated.

00:30:08.000 --> 00:30:11.000
Yeah, that's a lot of stuff going on.

00:30:11.000 --> 00:30:14.000
And I think the interest is awesome, right?

00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:18.000
I mean, there's just a different level of problems.

00:30:18.000 --> 00:30:21.000
I feel like you can take on, you know,

00:30:21.000 --> 00:30:25.000
I got this entire week and that's my job to make this work

00:30:25.000 --> 00:30:29.000
rather than I've got two hours and I can't really take on a huge project

00:30:29.000 --> 00:30:33.000
and so I'll work on the smaller improvements or whatever.

00:30:33.000 --> 00:30:37.000
Yeah, but I think many people know,

00:30:37.000 --> 00:30:41.000
but I haven't been involved day-to-day in Pandas since 2013.

00:30:41.000 --> 00:30:43.000
So that's getting on.

00:30:43.000 --> 00:30:45.000
That's a lot of years.

00:30:45.000 --> 00:30:50.000
You know, I still talk to the Pandas contributors.

00:30:50.000 --> 00:30:56.000
We had a Pandas meetup, core developer meetup here in Nashville pre-COVID.

00:30:56.000 --> 00:30:59.000
I think it was in 2019 maybe.

00:30:59.000 --> 00:31:03.000
So I'm still in active contact with the Pandas developers,

00:31:03.000 --> 00:31:08.000
but it's been a different team of people leading the project.

00:31:08.000 --> 00:31:11.000
It's taken on a life of its own, which is amazing.

00:31:11.000 --> 00:31:16.000
That's exactly, as a project creator, that's exactly what you want.

00:31:16.000 --> 00:31:20.000
It's to not be beholden to the project that you created

00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:26.000
and forced and have to be responsible for it

00:31:26.000 --> 00:31:30.000
and take care of it for the rest of your life.

00:31:30.000 --> 00:31:34.000
But if you look at a lot of the most intensive community development

00:31:34.000 --> 00:31:39.000
has happened since I moved on to work on other projects.

00:31:39.000 --> 00:31:42.000
So now the project has, I don't know the exact count,

00:31:42.000 --> 00:31:45.000
but it's had thousands of contributors.

00:31:45.000 --> 00:31:48.000
So to have thousands of different unique individuals

00:31:48.000 --> 00:31:53.000
contributing to an open source project, it's a big deal.

00:31:53.000 --> 00:31:56.000
I don't know what it says on the bottom of GitHub.

00:31:56.000 --> 00:32:00.000
It says, you know, 3,200 contributors,

00:32:00.000 --> 00:32:03.000
but that's maybe not even the full story

00:32:03.000 --> 00:32:08.000
because sometimes people don't have their email address associated

00:32:08.000 --> 00:32:10.000
with their GitHub profile.

00:32:10.000 --> 00:32:12.000
And how GitHub counts contributors,

00:32:12.000 --> 00:32:15.000
I would say probably the true number is closer to 4,000.

00:32:15.000 --> 00:32:16.000
Wow.

00:32:16.000 --> 00:32:21.000
Yeah, but I think that's a testament to the core team

00:32:21.000 --> 00:32:23.000
and all the outreach that they've done

00:32:23.000 --> 00:32:28.000
and making the project accessible and easy to contribute to.

00:32:28.000 --> 00:32:32.000
Because if you go and try to make a pull request to a project,

00:32:32.000 --> 00:32:35.000
there's many different ways that you can fail.

00:32:35.000 --> 00:32:38.000
So either the project is technically,

00:32:38.000 --> 00:32:42.000
there's issues with the build system or the developer tooling,

00:32:42.000 --> 00:32:44.000
and so you struggle with the developer tooling.

00:32:44.000 --> 00:32:47.000
And so if you aren't working on it every day and every night,

00:32:47.000 --> 00:32:50.000
you can't make heads or tails of how the developer tools work.

00:32:50.000 --> 00:32:53.000
But then there's also the level of accessibility

00:32:53.000 --> 00:32:55.000
of the core development team.

00:32:55.000 --> 00:32:59.000
If they aren't there to support you in getting involved in the project

00:32:59.000 --> 00:33:04.000
and learning how it works and creating documentation to be viewed

00:33:04.000 --> 00:33:06.000
and what's expected of you,

00:33:06.000 --> 00:33:08.000
that can also be a source of frustration

00:33:08.000 --> 00:33:11.000
where people churn out of the project

00:33:11.000 --> 00:33:15.000
because it's too hard to find their sea legs.

00:33:15.000 --> 00:33:23.000
And maybe also sometimes development teams are unfriendly or unhelpful

00:33:23.000 --> 00:33:29.000
or they make others feel like they're annoyed with them

00:33:29.000 --> 00:33:31.000
or they're wasting their time or something.

00:33:31.000 --> 00:33:34.000
It's like, I don't want to look at this pull request

00:33:34.000 --> 00:33:38.000
and give you feedback because I could do it more quickly by myself or something.

00:33:38.000 --> 00:33:41.000
Sometimes you see that in open source projects.

00:33:41.000 --> 00:33:47.000
But they've created a very welcoming environment,

00:33:47.000 --> 00:33:52.000
and I think the contribution numbers speak for themselves.

00:33:52.000 --> 00:33:53.000
They definitely do.

00:33:53.000 --> 00:33:56.000
Maybe the last thing before we move on to the other stuff you're working on,

00:33:56.000 --> 00:34:01.000
but the other interesting GitHub statistic here

00:34:01.000 --> 00:34:05.000
is the used by 1.6 million projects.

00:34:05.000 --> 00:34:07.000
I don't know if I've ever seen it used by that high.

00:34:07.000 --> 00:34:11.000
There's probably some that are higher, but not many.

00:34:11.000 --> 00:34:17.000
Yeah, it's a lot of projects.

00:34:17.000 --> 00:34:21.000
I think it's interesting.

00:34:21.000 --> 00:34:27.000
I think it's, like many projects,

00:34:27.000 --> 00:34:31.000
it's reached a point where it's an essential and assumed part

00:34:31.000 --> 00:34:35.000
of many people's toolkit.

00:34:36.000 --> 00:34:39.000
The first thing that they write at the top of a file that they're working on

00:34:39.000 --> 00:34:45.000
is import pandas as PD or import NumPy as PD.

00:34:51.000 --> 00:34:54.000
I think one of the reasons why pandas has gotten so popular

00:34:54.000 --> 00:34:59.000
is that it is beneficial to the community,

00:34:59.000 --> 00:35:05.000
to the Python community, to have fewer solutions.

00:35:05.000 --> 00:35:07.000
Kind of the zen of Python, there should be one

00:35:07.000 --> 00:35:11.000
and preferably only one obvious way to do things.

00:35:11.000 --> 00:35:15.000
If there were 10 different pandas-like projects,

00:35:15.000 --> 00:35:19.000
that creates skill portability problems.

00:35:19.000 --> 00:35:21.000
It's just easier if everyone says,

00:35:21.000 --> 00:35:23.000
oh, pandas is the thing that we use.

00:35:23.000 --> 00:35:26.000
Change jobs, and you can take all your skills,

00:35:26.000 --> 00:35:28.000
like how to use pandas with you.

00:35:28.000 --> 00:35:31.000
I think that's also one of the reasons why Python

00:35:31.000 --> 00:35:33.000
has become so successful in the business world

00:35:33.000 --> 00:35:37.000
is because you can teach somebody,

00:35:37.000 --> 00:35:39.000
even without a lot of programming experience,

00:35:39.000 --> 00:35:41.000
how to use Python, how to use pandas,

00:35:41.000 --> 00:35:47.000
and become productive doing basic work very quickly.

00:35:47.000 --> 00:35:52.000
One of the solutions, I remember back in the early 2010s,

00:35:52.000 --> 00:35:55.000
there were a lot of articles and talks about

00:35:55.000 --> 00:35:57.000
how to address the data science shortage.

00:35:58.000 --> 00:36:08.000
My belief, and I gave a talk at Web Summit in Dublin in 2000,

00:36:08.000 --> 00:36:13.000
gosh, maybe 2017, I have to look exactly.

00:36:13.000 --> 00:36:18.000
But basically, it was the data scientist shortage,

00:36:18.000 --> 00:36:20.000
and my thesis was always,

00:36:20.000 --> 00:36:22.000
we should make it easier to be a data scientist,

00:36:22.000 --> 00:36:25.000
or lower the bar for what sort of skills

00:36:25.000 --> 00:36:29.000
you have to master before you can do productive work

00:36:29.000 --> 00:36:31.000
in a business setting.

00:36:31.000 --> 00:36:34.000
I think the fact that there is just pandas,

00:36:34.000 --> 00:36:37.000
and that's the one thing that people have to learn how to use,

00:36:37.000 --> 00:36:41.000
is their essential starting point for doing any data work,

00:36:41.000 --> 00:36:45.000
has also led to this piling on of people being motivated

00:36:45.000 --> 00:36:47.000
to make this one thing better,

00:36:47.000 --> 00:36:50.000
because you make improvements to pandas,

00:36:50.000 --> 00:36:52.000
and they benefit millions of projects

00:36:52.000 --> 00:36:54.000
and millions of people around the world.

00:36:55.000 --> 00:36:58.000
So it's like a steady snowballing effect.

00:37:00.000 --> 00:37:03.000
I agree with you, and I think doing data science

00:37:03.000 --> 00:37:05.000
is getting easier.

00:37:05.000 --> 00:37:08.000
We've got a lot of interesting frameworks and tools,

00:37:08.000 --> 00:37:11.000
for Python, one of them, right,

00:37:11.000 --> 00:37:16.000
that makes it easier to share and run your code.

00:37:16.000 --> 00:37:22.000
Yeah, so I think the Shiny for Python,

00:37:22.000 --> 00:37:24.000
Streamlet, Dash,

00:37:24.000 --> 00:37:27.000
like these different interactive data application

00:37:27.000 --> 00:37:28.000
publishing frameworks,

00:37:28.000 --> 00:37:32.000
you can go from a few lines of pandas code,

00:37:32.000 --> 00:37:35.000
loading some data and doing some analysis and visualization

00:37:35.000 --> 00:37:39.000
to pushing that as an interactive website

00:37:39.000 --> 00:37:41.000
without having to know how to use

00:37:41.000 --> 00:37:44.000
any web development frameworks or Node.js

00:37:44.000 --> 00:37:46.000
or anything like that.

00:37:46.000 --> 00:37:49.000
And so to be able to get up and running

00:37:49.000 --> 00:37:54.000
and build a working interactive web application

00:37:54.000 --> 00:37:56.000
that's powered by Python,

00:37:56.000 --> 00:38:00.000
yeah, it's a game changer in terms of shortening

00:38:00.000 --> 00:38:03.000
end-to-end development life cycles.

00:38:03.000 --> 00:38:07.000
What do you think about JupyterLite

00:38:07.000 --> 00:38:13.000
and these PyOxidize and basically Jupyter

00:38:13.000 --> 00:38:16.000
in a browser type of things?

00:38:16.000 --> 00:38:18.000
Yeah.

00:38:18.000 --> 00:38:20.000
WebAssembly and all that.

00:38:20.000 --> 00:38:26.000
Yeah, so I'm definitely very excited about it,

00:38:26.000 --> 00:38:28.000
been following WebAssembly in general,

00:38:28.000 --> 00:38:30.000
and so I guess some people listening

00:38:30.000 --> 00:38:33.000
will know about WebAssembly,

00:38:33.000 --> 00:38:37.000
but basically it's a portable machine code

00:38:37.000 --> 00:38:40.000
that can be compiled and executed

00:38:40.000 --> 00:38:43.000
within your browser in a sandbox environment,

00:38:43.000 --> 00:38:46.000
so it protects against security issues

00:38:46.000 --> 00:38:50.000
and prevents the person who wrote the WebAssembly code

00:38:50.000 --> 00:38:53.000
from doing something malicious on your machine,

00:38:53.000 --> 00:38:55.000
which is very important.

00:38:55.000 --> 00:38:58.000
Won't necessarily stop them from mining cryptocurrency

00:38:58.000 --> 00:39:00.000
while you have the browser tab open.

00:39:00.000 --> 00:39:02.000
That's a whole separate problem.

00:39:02.000 --> 00:39:04.000
But yeah, I think it's enabled us

00:39:04.000 --> 00:39:07.000
to run the whole scientific Python stack,

00:39:07.000 --> 00:39:09.000
including Jupyter and NumPy and Pandas

00:39:09.000 --> 00:39:13.000
totally in the browser without having a client and server

00:39:13.000 --> 00:39:17.000
and needing to run a container someplace in the cloud.

00:39:17.000 --> 00:39:22.000
And so I think in terms of creating application deployment,

00:39:22.000 --> 00:39:26.000
so like being able to deploy an interactive data application,

00:39:26.000 --> 00:39:28.000
like with Shiny, for example,

00:39:28.000 --> 00:39:30.000
without needing to have a server,

00:39:30.000 --> 00:39:33.000
that's actually pretty amazing.

00:39:33.000 --> 00:39:39.000
And so I think that simplifies and opens up new use cases,

00:39:39.000 --> 00:39:41.000
like new application architectures

00:39:41.000 --> 00:39:44.000
and makes things a lot easier.

00:39:44.000 --> 00:39:46.000
Because setting up and running a server

00:39:46.000 --> 00:39:48.000
creates brittleness, like it has cost.

00:39:48.000 --> 00:39:53.000
And so if the browser is doubling as your server process,

00:39:53.000 --> 00:39:56.000
I think that's really cool.

00:39:56.000 --> 00:39:59.000
You also have other projects like DuckDB,

00:39:59.000 --> 00:40:05.000
which is a high-performance embeddable analytic SQL engine.

00:40:05.000 --> 00:40:08.000
And so now with DuckDB compiled to Wasm,

00:40:08.000 --> 00:40:11.000
you can get a high-performance database

00:40:11.000 --> 00:40:12.000
running in your browser.

00:40:12.000 --> 00:40:15.000
And so you can get low-latency interactive queries

00:40:15.000 --> 00:40:17.000
and interactive dashboards.

00:40:17.000 --> 00:40:23.000
And so WebAssembly has opened up

00:40:23.000 --> 00:40:26.000
this whole kind of new world of possibilities,

00:40:26.000 --> 00:40:31.000
and so it's transformative, I think.

00:40:31.000 --> 00:40:33.000
I think for Python in particular,

00:40:33.000 --> 00:40:34.000
you mentioned PyDyed,

00:40:34.000 --> 00:40:38.000
which is kind of a whole package stack.

00:40:38.000 --> 00:40:43.000
So it's like a framework for build and build and packaging

00:40:43.000 --> 00:40:45.000
and basically building an application

00:40:45.000 --> 00:40:47.000
and managing its dependencies

00:40:47.000 --> 00:40:50.000
so you could create a WebAssembly version

00:40:50.000 --> 00:40:54.000
of your application to be deployed like this.

00:40:54.000 --> 00:40:58.000
But yeah, so I think one of the PyDyed,

00:40:58.000 --> 00:41:01.000
either the PyDyed main creator or maintainer went to Anaconda,

00:41:01.000 --> 00:41:03.000
and they created PyScript,

00:41:03.000 --> 00:41:05.000
which is another attempt to make it even easier

00:41:05.000 --> 00:41:13.000
to use Python to create web applications,

00:41:13.000 --> 00:41:15.000
interactive web applications.

00:41:15.000 --> 00:41:18.000
And yeah, so there's so many cool things here.

00:41:18.000 --> 00:41:20.000
Like in the R community, they have WebR,

00:41:20.000 --> 00:41:23.000
which is similar to PyScript and PyDyed in some ways,

00:41:23.000 --> 00:41:26.000
like compiling the whole R stack to WebAssembly.

00:41:26.000 --> 00:41:28.000
There was just an article I saw on Hacker News

00:41:28.000 --> 00:41:31.000
where they worked on figuring out

00:41:31.000 --> 00:41:34.000
how to trick LLVM into compiling Fortran code,

00:41:34.000 --> 00:41:37.000
like legacy Fortran code, to WebAssembly

00:41:37.000 --> 00:41:40.000
because when you're talking about all of this

00:41:40.000 --> 00:41:42.000
scientific computing stack,

00:41:42.000 --> 00:41:43.000
you need the linear algebra

00:41:43.000 --> 00:41:46.000
and all of the 40 years of Fortran code

00:41:46.000 --> 00:41:48.000
that have been built to support scientific applications.

00:41:48.000 --> 00:41:54.000
You need all that to compile too and run in the browser.

00:41:54.000 --> 00:41:57.000
Yeah, that's pretty wild to think of putting that in there,

00:41:57.000 --> 00:41:58.000
but very useful.

00:41:58.000 --> 00:42:01.000
I didn't realize that you could use DuckDB

00:42:01.000 --> 00:42:03.000
as a WebAssembly component.

00:42:03.000 --> 00:42:04.000
That's pretty cool.

00:42:04.000 --> 00:42:06.000
Yeah, there's a company.

00:42:06.000 --> 00:42:08.000
I'm not an investor or plugging them or anything,

00:42:08.000 --> 00:42:10.000
but it's called Evidence.dev,

00:42:10.000 --> 00:42:16.000
and it's like a whole business intelligence,

00:42:16.000 --> 00:42:18.000
open source business intelligence application

00:42:18.000 --> 00:42:20.000
that's powered by DuckDB.

00:42:20.000 --> 00:42:25.000
And so if you have data that fits in the browser,

00:42:25.000 --> 00:42:27.000
to have a whole interactive dashboard

00:42:27.000 --> 00:42:29.000
or to be able to do business intelligence

00:42:29.000 --> 00:42:35.000
fully in the browser with no need of a server,

00:42:35.000 --> 00:42:39.000
it's very, very cool.

00:42:39.000 --> 00:42:43.000
I've been following DuckDB since the early days,

00:42:43.000 --> 00:42:48.000
and my company, Voltron Data,

00:42:48.000 --> 00:42:51.000
we became members of the DuckDB Foundation

00:42:51.000 --> 00:42:55.000
and actively built a relationship with DuckDB Labs

00:42:55.000 --> 00:42:59.000
so we could help accelerate progress in this space

00:42:59.000 --> 00:43:04.000
because I think the impact is so immense,

00:43:04.000 --> 00:43:09.000
and it's hard to predict what people are going to build

00:43:09.000 --> 00:43:11.000
with all this stuff.

00:43:11.000 --> 00:43:14.000
And so that was all with, I guess,

00:43:14.000 --> 00:43:16.000
going back 15 years ago to Python,

00:43:17.000 --> 00:43:20.000
one of the reasons I became so passionate

00:43:20.000 --> 00:43:25.000
about building stuff for Python was about,

00:43:25.000 --> 00:43:27.000
I think the way that Peter Wang puts it

00:43:27.000 --> 00:43:30.000
is giving people superpowers.

00:43:30.000 --> 00:43:34.000
So we want to enable people to build things

00:43:34.000 --> 00:43:36.000
with much less code and much less time.

00:43:36.000 --> 00:43:40.000
And so by making things that much more accessible,

00:43:40.000 --> 00:43:42.000
that much easier to do,

00:43:42.000 --> 00:43:45.000
and the mantra in Pandas was how do we make things,

00:43:45.000 --> 00:43:47.000
one line of code, that must be easy,

00:43:47.000 --> 00:43:49.000
it's one line of code, one line of code,

00:43:49.000 --> 00:43:54.000
it must be, make this as terse and simple as possible

00:43:54.000 --> 00:43:56.000
so that you can move on and focus on building

00:43:56.000 --> 00:43:58.000
the more interesting parts of your application

00:43:58.000 --> 00:44:01.000
rather than struggling with how to read a CSV file

00:44:01.000 --> 00:44:08.000
or how to do whichever data munging technique

00:44:08.000 --> 00:44:12.000
that you need for your dataset.

00:44:12.000 --> 00:44:14.000
Maybe an interesting mental model for DuckDB

00:44:14.000 --> 00:44:16.000
is kind of an equivalent to SQLite,

00:44:16.000 --> 00:44:18.000
but more analytics database for folks,

00:44:18.000 --> 00:44:21.000
in process and things, right?

00:44:21.000 --> 00:44:22.000
What do you think?

00:44:22.000 --> 00:44:24.000
Yeah, so DuckDB is like SQLite,

00:44:24.000 --> 00:44:27.000
and in fact it can run the whole SQLite test suite,

00:44:27.000 --> 00:44:29.000
I believe, so it's a full database,

00:44:29.000 --> 00:44:34.000
but it's for analytic processing,

00:44:34.000 --> 00:44:36.000
so it's optimized for analytic processing

00:44:36.000 --> 00:44:39.000
and as compared with SQLite,

00:44:39.000 --> 00:44:44.000
which is not, it's not designed for data processing.

00:44:44.000 --> 00:44:45.000
Yeah, cool.

00:44:45.000 --> 00:44:47.000
All right, well, let's talk about some things

00:44:47.000 --> 00:44:51.000
that you're working on beyond Pandas.

00:44:51.000 --> 00:44:54.000
You talked about Apache Arrow earlier.

00:44:54.000 --> 00:44:58.000
What are you doing with Arrow and how does it fit in your world?

00:44:58.000 --> 00:45:03.000
Yeah, so the back story there was,

00:45:03.000 --> 00:45:05.000
I don't know if you can hear the sirens

00:45:05.000 --> 00:45:07.000
in downtown Nashville, but...

00:45:07.000 --> 00:45:08.000
No, actually.

00:45:08.000 --> 00:45:09.000
That's good.

00:45:09.000 --> 00:45:12.000
The microphone filters it out pretty well.

00:45:12.000 --> 00:45:14.000
Yay for dynamic microphones.

00:45:14.000 --> 00:45:15.000
They're amazing.

00:45:15.000 --> 00:45:21.000
Yeah, so around the mid-2010s, 2015,

00:45:21.000 --> 00:45:26.000
I started working at Cloudera,

00:45:26.000 --> 00:45:29.000
which is a company that was one of the pioneers

00:45:29.000 --> 00:45:33.000
in the big data ecosystem,

00:45:33.000 --> 00:45:38.000
and I had spent several years working on,

00:45:38.000 --> 00:45:40.000
five, six years working on Pandas,

00:45:40.000 --> 00:45:43.000
and so I had gone through the experience

00:45:43.000 --> 00:45:46.000
of building Pandas from top to bottom,

00:45:46.000 --> 00:45:50.000
and it was this full stack system

00:45:50.000 --> 00:45:53.000
that had its own mini query engine,

00:45:53.000 --> 00:45:56.000
all of its own algorithms and data structures

00:45:56.000 --> 00:45:59.000
and all the stuff that we had to build from scratch,

00:45:59.000 --> 00:46:01.000
and I started thinking about,

00:46:01.000 --> 00:46:03.000
what if it was possible to build

00:46:03.000 --> 00:46:06.000
some of the underlying computing technology

00:46:06.000 --> 00:46:09.000
like data readers, like file readers,

00:46:09.000 --> 00:46:14.000
all the algorithms that power the core components of Pandas,

00:46:14.000 --> 00:46:18.000
like group operations, aggregations, filtering, selection,

00:46:18.000 --> 00:46:19.000
all those things.

00:46:19.000 --> 00:46:23.000
What if it were possible to have a general-purpose library

00:46:23.000 --> 00:46:25.000
that isn't specific to Python,

00:46:25.000 --> 00:46:28.000
but is really, really fast, really efficient,

00:46:28.000 --> 00:46:31.000
and has a large community building it

00:46:31.000 --> 00:46:34.000
so that you could take that code with you

00:46:34.000 --> 00:46:36.000
and use it to build many different types of libraries,

00:46:36.000 --> 00:46:38.000
not just data frame libraries,

00:46:38.000 --> 00:46:42.000
but also database engines and stream processing engines

00:46:42.000 --> 00:46:44.000
and all kinds of things,

00:46:44.000 --> 00:46:47.000
and so that was kind of what was in my mind

00:46:47.000 --> 00:46:49.000
when I started getting interested

00:46:49.000 --> 00:46:51.000
in what turned into Arrow,

00:46:51.000 --> 00:46:54.000
and one of the problems we realized we needed to solve,

00:46:54.000 --> 00:46:57.000
this was like a group of other open-source developers and me,

00:46:57.000 --> 00:47:01.000
was that we needed to create a way to represent data

00:47:01.000 --> 00:47:05.000
that was not tied to a specific programming language

00:47:05.000 --> 00:47:09.000
and that could be used for a very efficient interchange

00:47:09.000 --> 00:47:11.000
between components,

00:47:11.000 --> 00:47:14.000
and the idea is that you would have this immutable,

00:47:14.000 --> 00:47:17.000
like this kind of constant data structure,

00:47:17.000 --> 00:47:20.000
which is like it's the same in every programming language,

00:47:20.000 --> 00:47:22.000
and then you can use that as the basis

00:47:22.000 --> 00:47:24.000
for writing all of your algorithms.

00:47:24.000 --> 00:47:25.000
So as long as it's Arrow,

00:47:25.000 --> 00:47:27.000
you have these reusable algorithms

00:47:27.000 --> 00:47:30.000
that process Arrow data.

00:47:30.000 --> 00:47:33.000
So we started with building the Arrow format

00:47:33.000 --> 00:47:34.000
and standardizing it,

00:47:34.000 --> 00:47:39.000
and then we built a whole ecosystem of components,

00:47:39.000 --> 00:47:40.000
like library components

00:47:40.000 --> 00:47:42.000
and different programming languages

00:47:42.000 --> 00:47:46.000
for building applications that use the Arrow format,

00:47:46.000 --> 00:47:51.000
so that includes not only tools for building

00:47:51.000 --> 00:47:53.000
and interacting with the data,

00:47:53.000 --> 00:47:54.000
but also file readers,

00:47:54.000 --> 00:47:58.000
so you can read CSV files and JSON data and Parquet files,

00:47:58.000 --> 00:48:01.000
read data out of database systems.

00:48:01.000 --> 00:48:02.000
Wherever the data comes from,

00:48:02.000 --> 00:48:05.000
we want to have an efficient way to get it into the Arrow format,

00:48:05.000 --> 00:48:10.000
and then we moved on to building data processing engines

00:48:10.000 --> 00:48:13.000
that are native to the Arrow format,

00:48:13.000 --> 00:48:16.000
so that Arrow goes in, the data's processed,

00:48:16.000 --> 00:48:18.000
Arrow goes out.

00:48:18.000 --> 00:48:19.000
So DuckDB, for example,

00:48:19.000 --> 00:48:22.000
supports Arrow as a preferred input format

00:48:22.000 --> 00:48:26.000
and DuckDB is more or less Arrow-like in its internals.

00:48:26.000 --> 00:48:30.000
It has Arrow format plus a number of extensions

00:48:30.000 --> 00:48:34.000
that are DuckDB-specific for better performance

00:48:34.000 --> 00:48:38.000
within the context of DuckDB.

00:48:38.000 --> 00:48:40.000
And so in numerous communities,

00:48:40.000 --> 00:48:41.000
so there's the Rust community,

00:48:41.000 --> 00:48:43.000
which has built DataFusion,

00:48:43.000 --> 00:48:47.000
which is an execution engine for Arrow,

00:48:47.000 --> 00:48:49.000
SQL engine for Arrow.

00:48:49.000 --> 00:48:51.000
And so, yeah, we've kind of looked

00:48:51.000 --> 00:48:52.000
at the different layers of the stack,

00:48:52.000 --> 00:48:57.000
like data access, computing, data transport,

00:48:57.000 --> 00:48:58.000
everything under the sun,

00:48:58.000 --> 00:49:00.000
and then we've built libraries

00:49:00.000 --> 00:49:03.000
that are across many different programming languages

00:49:03.000 --> 00:49:05.000
that you can pick and choose the pieces

00:49:05.000 --> 00:49:07.000
that you need to build your system.

00:49:07.000 --> 00:49:10.000
And the goal ultimately was that we,

00:49:10.000 --> 00:49:12.000
in the future, which is now,

00:49:12.000 --> 00:49:15.000
we don't want people to have to reinvent the wheel

00:49:15.000 --> 00:49:17.000
whenever they're building something like Pandas,

00:49:17.000 --> 00:49:20.000
that they could just pick up these off-the-shelf components,

00:49:20.000 --> 00:49:23.000
they can design the developer experience,

00:49:23.000 --> 00:49:25.000
the user experience that they want to create,

00:49:25.000 --> 00:49:28.000
and they can get built.

00:49:28.000 --> 00:49:30.000
So if you were building Pandas now,

00:49:30.000 --> 00:49:33.000
you could build a Pandas-like library

00:49:33.000 --> 00:49:37.000
based on the Arrow components in much less time,

00:49:37.000 --> 00:49:40.000
and it would be fast and efficient

00:49:40.000 --> 00:49:42.000
and interoperable with the whole ecosystem

00:49:42.000 --> 00:49:44.000
of other projects that use Arrow.

00:49:44.000 --> 00:49:46.000
So it's very cool.

00:49:46.000 --> 00:49:49.000
I mean, it was really ambitious.

00:49:49.000 --> 00:49:51.000
In some ways obvious to people,

00:49:51.000 --> 00:49:52.000
they would hear about Arrow,

00:49:52.000 --> 00:49:54.000
and they'd say, that sounds obvious.

00:49:54.000 --> 00:49:56.000
Like, clearly we should have a universal way

00:49:56.000 --> 00:49:58.000
of transporting data between systems

00:49:58.000 --> 00:50:00.000
and processing it in memory.

00:50:00.000 --> 00:50:02.000
Why hasn't this been done in the past?

00:50:02.000 --> 00:50:04.000
And it turns out that, as is true

00:50:04.000 --> 00:50:08.000
with many open-source software problems,

00:50:08.000 --> 00:50:11.000
that many of these problems are,

00:50:11.000 --> 00:50:12.000
the social problems are harder

00:50:12.000 --> 00:50:13.000
than the technical problems.

00:50:13.000 --> 00:50:17.000
And so if you can solve the kind of people coordination

00:50:18.000 --> 00:50:20.000
and consensus problems,

00:50:20.000 --> 00:50:21.000
solving the technical issues

00:50:21.000 --> 00:50:23.000
is much easier by comparison.

00:50:23.000 --> 00:50:25.000
So I think we were lucky in that

00:50:25.000 --> 00:50:29.000
we found the right group of people,

00:50:29.000 --> 00:50:31.000
the right personalities,

00:50:31.000 --> 00:50:33.000
where we were able to,

00:50:33.000 --> 00:50:36.000
as soon as I met Jacques Nadeau,

00:50:36.000 --> 00:50:38.000
who had been at MapR

00:50:38.000 --> 00:50:41.000
and was working on his startup, Dremio,

00:50:41.000 --> 00:50:43.000
I knew instantly when I met Jacques Nadeau,

00:50:43.000 --> 00:50:45.000
it's like, I can work,

00:50:45.000 --> 00:50:47.000
it's like him,

00:50:47.000 --> 00:50:49.000
he's going to help me make this happen.

00:50:49.000 --> 00:50:50.000
When I met Julien Ledam,

00:50:50.000 --> 00:50:52.000
who had also co-created Parquet,

00:50:52.000 --> 00:50:54.000
I was like, yes,

00:50:54.000 --> 00:50:56.000
we are going to make this,

00:50:56.000 --> 00:50:57.000
I found the right people,

00:50:57.000 --> 00:50:59.000
we are going to make this happen.

00:50:59.000 --> 00:51:02.000
So it's been a labor of love

00:51:02.000 --> 00:51:06.000
and much work and stress and everything.

00:51:10.000 --> 00:51:12.000
I've been working on things,

00:51:12.000 --> 00:51:14.000
circling, with Aero as the sun,

00:51:14.000 --> 00:51:17.000
I've been building satellites and moons and planets,

00:51:17.000 --> 00:51:20.000
circling the Aero sun

00:51:20.000 --> 00:51:22.000
over the last eight years or so,

00:51:22.000 --> 00:51:25.000
and that's kept me pretty busy.

00:51:25.000 --> 00:51:28.000
Yeah, it's only getting more exciting and interesting.

00:51:28.000 --> 00:51:30.000
Over here it says,

00:51:30.000 --> 00:51:33.000
it uses efficient analytic operations

00:51:33.000 --> 00:51:36.000
on modern hardware like CPUs and GPUs.

00:51:36.000 --> 00:51:39.000
One of the big challenges of Python

00:51:39.000 --> 00:51:40.000
has been the GIL,

00:51:40.000 --> 00:51:41.000
also one of its big benefits,

00:51:41.000 --> 00:51:42.000
but one of its challenges

00:51:42.000 --> 00:51:45.000
when you get to multicore or computational stuff

00:51:45.000 --> 00:51:46.000
has been the GIL.

00:51:46.000 --> 00:51:48.000
What's the story here?

00:51:48.000 --> 00:51:52.000
Yeah, so in AeroLand,

00:51:52.000 --> 00:51:55.000
when we're talking about analytic efficiency,

00:51:55.000 --> 00:52:00.000
it mainly has to do with the underlying,

00:52:00.000 --> 00:52:03.000
how a modern CPU works

00:52:03.000 --> 00:52:06.000
or how a GPU works.

00:52:06.000 --> 00:52:08.000
And so when the data is arranged

00:52:08.000 --> 00:52:10.000
in column-oriented format,

00:52:10.000 --> 00:52:14.000
that enables the data

00:52:14.000 --> 00:52:16.000
to be moved efficiently

00:52:16.000 --> 00:52:19.000
through the CPU cache pipelines,

00:52:19.000 --> 00:52:22.000
so the data is made available efficiently

00:52:22.000 --> 00:52:25.000
to the CPU cores.

00:52:25.000 --> 00:52:28.000
And so we spent a lot of energy in Aero

00:52:28.000 --> 00:52:29.000
making decisions,

00:52:29.000 --> 00:52:32.000
firstly, to enable very cache-efficient,

00:52:32.000 --> 00:52:36.000
like CPU cache or GPU cache-efficient analytics

00:52:36.000 --> 00:52:38.000
on the data.

00:52:38.000 --> 00:52:40.000
And so we were kind of always,

00:52:40.000 --> 00:52:41.000
we were deciding,

00:52:41.000 --> 00:52:43.000
we would break ties and make decisions

00:52:43.000 --> 00:52:45.000
based on what's going to be more efficient

00:52:45.000 --> 00:52:47.000
for the computer chip.

00:52:47.000 --> 00:52:51.000
The other thing is that modern,

00:52:51.000 --> 00:52:53.000
and this is true with GPUs,

00:52:53.000 --> 00:52:56.000
which have a different parallelism model

00:52:56.000 --> 00:53:02.000
or a different kind of multicore parallelism model

00:53:02.000 --> 00:53:03.000
than CPUs,

00:53:03.000 --> 00:53:04.000
but in CPUs,

00:53:04.000 --> 00:53:06.000
they've focused on adding

00:53:07.000 --> 00:53:08.000
what are called

00:53:08.000 --> 00:53:10.000
single instruction multiple data,

00:53:10.000 --> 00:53:11.000
intrinsic,

00:53:11.000 --> 00:53:14.000
like built-in operations in the processor

00:53:14.000 --> 00:53:16.000
where now you can process

00:53:16.000 --> 00:53:19.000
up to 512 bytes of data

00:53:19.000 --> 00:53:21.000
in a single CPU instruction.

00:53:21.000 --> 00:53:24.000
And so that's like,

00:53:24.000 --> 00:53:25.000
my brain's doing the math right,

00:53:25.000 --> 00:53:27.000
like 16 32-bit floats

00:53:27.000 --> 00:53:30.000
or eight 64-bit integers

00:53:30.000 --> 00:53:32.000
in a single cycle.

00:53:32.000 --> 00:53:34.000
There's like intrinsic operations

00:53:34.000 --> 00:53:36.000
You could multiply this number by that one,

00:53:36.000 --> 00:53:38.000
multiply that number to these eight things

00:53:38.000 --> 00:53:39.000
all at once,

00:53:39.000 --> 00:53:40.000
something like that.

00:53:40.000 --> 00:53:41.000
That's right, yeah.

00:53:41.000 --> 00:53:42.000
Or you might say like,

00:53:42.000 --> 00:53:43.000
oh, I have a bit mask

00:53:43.000 --> 00:53:45.000
and I want to select,

00:53:45.000 --> 00:53:46.000
I want to gather

00:53:46.000 --> 00:53:49.000
like the one bits that are set

00:53:49.000 --> 00:53:52.000
in this bit mask

00:53:52.000 --> 00:53:54.000
from this array of integers.

00:53:54.000 --> 00:53:56.000
And so there's like a gather instruction

00:53:56.000 --> 00:54:00.000
which allows you to select a subset,

00:54:01.000 --> 00:54:04.000
a sort of SIMD vector of integers

00:54:04.000 --> 00:54:05.000
using a bit mask.

00:54:05.000 --> 00:54:07.000
And so that turns out to be

00:54:07.000 --> 00:54:09.000
a pretty critical operation

00:54:09.000 --> 00:54:12.000
in certain data analytic workloads.

00:54:12.000 --> 00:54:14.000
So yeah, we were really,

00:54:14.000 --> 00:54:16.000
we wanted to have a data format

00:54:16.000 --> 00:54:20.000
that was essentially future-proofed

00:54:20.000 --> 00:54:21.000
in the sense that

00:54:21.000 --> 00:54:24.000
it's ideal for the coming wave,

00:54:24.000 --> 00:54:26.000
like current generation of CPUs,

00:54:26.000 --> 00:54:29.000
but also given that a lot of processing

00:54:29.000 --> 00:54:32.000
is moving to GPUs and to FPGAs

00:54:32.000 --> 00:54:35.000
and to custom silicon,

00:54:35.000 --> 00:54:36.000
like we wanted Arrow

00:54:36.000 --> 00:54:39.000
to be usable there as well.

00:54:39.000 --> 00:54:41.000
And Arrow has been successfully

00:54:41.000 --> 00:54:43.000
used as the foundation

00:54:43.000 --> 00:54:45.000
of GPU computing libraries

00:54:45.000 --> 00:54:48.000
like we kind of at Voltron Data

00:54:48.000 --> 00:54:52.000
built a whole accelerator native,

00:54:52.000 --> 00:54:54.000
GPU native,

00:54:54.000 --> 00:54:56.000
scalable execution engine

00:54:56.000 --> 00:54:58.000
that's Arrow-based.

00:54:58.000 --> 00:55:00.000
And so I think the fact that we,

00:55:00.000 --> 00:55:01.000
that was our aspiration

00:55:01.000 --> 00:55:03.000
and we've been able to prove that out

00:55:03.000 --> 00:55:04.000
in real-world workloads

00:55:04.000 --> 00:55:06.000
and show the kinds of efficiency gains

00:55:06.000 --> 00:55:08.000
that you can get with

00:55:08.000 --> 00:55:11.000
using modern computing hardware correctly

00:55:11.000 --> 00:55:12.000
or at least as well

00:55:12.000 --> 00:55:14.000
as it's intended to be used.

00:55:14.000 --> 00:55:15.000
That's a big deal

00:55:15.000 --> 00:55:18.000
in terms of like making applications faster,

00:55:18.000 --> 00:55:20.000
reducing the carbon footprint

00:55:20.000 --> 00:55:21.000
of large-scale data workloads,

00:55:21.000 --> 00:55:23.000
things like that.

00:55:23.000 --> 00:55:25.000
Yeah, amazing.

00:55:25.000 --> 00:55:26.000
All right, let's see,

00:55:26.000 --> 00:55:27.000
what else have I got on deck here

00:55:27.000 --> 00:55:29.000
to talk to you about?

00:55:29.000 --> 00:55:31.000
Let's...

00:55:31.000 --> 00:55:33.000
Maybe we can talk about...

00:55:33.000 --> 00:55:34.000
We got a little time left.

00:55:34.000 --> 00:55:35.000
We got a couple of things to cover.

00:55:35.000 --> 00:55:37.000
Yeah, we can talk about this.

00:55:37.000 --> 00:55:38.000
Yeah, we could probably

00:55:38.000 --> 00:55:39.000
spend another hour talking.

00:55:39.000 --> 00:55:40.000
Yes, easy.

00:55:40.000 --> 00:55:43.000
I think one of the more interesting areas

00:55:43.000 --> 00:55:44.000
in recent years

00:55:44.000 --> 00:55:47.000
has been new DataFrame libraries

00:55:47.000 --> 00:55:49.000
and DataFrame APIs

00:55:49.000 --> 00:55:51.000
that transpile or compile

00:55:51.000 --> 00:55:52.000
to different,

00:55:52.000 --> 00:55:54.000
execute on different backends.

00:55:54.000 --> 00:55:55.000
And so around the time

00:55:55.000 --> 00:55:57.000
that I was helping start Arrow,

00:55:57.000 --> 00:55:59.000
I created this project called Ibis,

00:55:59.000 --> 00:56:01.000
which is basically

00:56:01.000 --> 00:56:03.000
a portable DataFrame API

00:56:03.000 --> 00:56:06.000
that knows how to generate SQL queries

00:56:06.000 --> 00:56:09.000
and compile to Pandas and Polars

00:56:09.000 --> 00:56:12.000
and different DataFrame backends.

00:56:12.000 --> 00:56:15.000
And the goal is to provide

00:56:15.000 --> 00:56:18.000
a really productive DataFrame API

00:56:18.000 --> 00:56:19.000
that gives you portability

00:56:19.000 --> 00:56:22.000
across different execution backends

00:56:22.000 --> 00:56:23.000
with the goal of enabling

00:56:23.000 --> 00:56:26.000
what we call the multi-engine data stack.

00:56:26.000 --> 00:56:27.000
So you aren't stuck

00:56:27.000 --> 00:56:29.000
with using one particular system

00:56:29.000 --> 00:56:31.000
because all of the code that you've written

00:56:31.000 --> 00:56:33.000
is specialized to that system.

00:56:33.000 --> 00:56:35.000
You have this tool, which...

00:56:35.000 --> 00:56:36.000
So maybe you could work with,

00:56:36.000 --> 00:56:38.000
you know, DuckDB on your laptop

00:56:38.000 --> 00:56:40.000
or Pandas or Polars

00:56:40.000 --> 00:56:42.000
with Ibis on your laptop.

00:56:42.000 --> 00:56:43.000
But if you have...

00:56:43.000 --> 00:56:44.000
If you need to run that workload

00:56:44.000 --> 00:56:45.000
someplace else,

00:56:45.000 --> 00:56:46.000
maybe with, you know,

00:56:46.000 --> 00:56:48.000
ClickHouse or BigQuery,

00:56:48.000 --> 00:56:50.000
or maybe it's a large big data workload

00:56:50.000 --> 00:56:52.000
that's too big to fit on your laptop

00:56:52.000 --> 00:56:54.000
and you need to use Spark SQL

00:56:54.000 --> 00:56:56.000
or something,

00:56:56.000 --> 00:56:57.000
that you can just ask Ibis,

00:56:57.000 --> 00:56:59.000
say, hey, I want to do the same thing

00:56:59.000 --> 00:57:01.000
on this larger dataset over here.

00:57:01.000 --> 00:57:03.000
And it has all the logic

00:57:03.000 --> 00:57:06.000
to generate the correct,

00:57:06.000 --> 00:57:07.000
you know, query representation

00:57:07.000 --> 00:57:08.000
and run that workload for you.

00:57:08.000 --> 00:57:10.000
So it's super useful.

00:57:10.000 --> 00:57:12.000
But there's a whole wave of, like,

00:57:12.000 --> 00:57:13.000
you know, work right now

00:57:13.000 --> 00:57:14.000
to help enable people

00:57:14.000 --> 00:57:17.000
to work in a Pandas-like way,

00:57:17.000 --> 00:57:19.000
but get work with big data

00:57:19.000 --> 00:57:21.000
or, you know, get better performance

00:57:21.000 --> 00:57:22.000
than Pandas,

00:57:22.000 --> 00:57:24.000
because Pandas is a Swiss Army knife

00:57:24.000 --> 00:57:26.000
but isn't a chainsaw,

00:57:26.000 --> 00:57:30.000
so it isn't...

00:57:30.000 --> 00:57:31.000
You know, if you were rebuilding Pandas

00:57:31.000 --> 00:57:32.000
from scratch,

00:57:32.000 --> 00:57:34.000
it would end up a lot...

00:57:34.000 --> 00:57:35.000
You know, there's areas

00:57:35.000 --> 00:57:36.000
of the projects

00:57:36.000 --> 00:57:37.000
that are more bloated

00:57:37.000 --> 00:57:39.000
or have performance overhead

00:57:39.000 --> 00:57:40.000
that's hard to get rid of.

00:57:40.000 --> 00:57:42.000
And so that's why you have, you know,

00:57:42.000 --> 00:57:44.000
Richie Fink started the Polars project,

00:57:44.000 --> 00:57:46.000
which is kind of a reimagining

00:57:46.000 --> 00:57:49.000
of Pandas data frames

00:57:50.000 --> 00:57:51.000
written in Rust

00:57:51.000 --> 00:57:53.000
and exposed in Python.

00:57:53.000 --> 00:57:55.000
And Polars, of course,

00:57:55.000 --> 00:57:57.000
is built on Apache Arrow

00:57:57.000 --> 00:57:59.000
at its core.

00:57:59.000 --> 00:58:00.000
So, you know,

00:58:00.000 --> 00:58:01.000
building an Arrow-native

00:58:01.000 --> 00:58:03.000
data frame library in Rust

00:58:03.000 --> 00:58:04.000
and, you know, all the benefits

00:58:04.000 --> 00:58:06.000
that come with, you know,

00:58:06.000 --> 00:58:08.000
building Python extensions in Rust,

00:58:08.000 --> 00:58:09.000
you know, you avoid the gill

00:58:09.000 --> 00:58:10.000
and you can manage

00:58:10.000 --> 00:58:11.000
the multithreading

00:58:11.000 --> 00:58:12.000
in a system's language,

00:58:12.000 --> 00:58:14.000
all that fun stuff.

00:58:14.000 --> 00:58:16.000
Yeah, when you're talking about Arrow

00:58:16.000 --> 00:58:18.000
and supporting different ways

00:58:18.000 --> 00:58:19.000
of using it and things being built on it,

00:58:19.000 --> 00:58:22.000
certainly Polars came to mind for me.

00:58:22.000 --> 00:58:24.000
You know, when you talk about Ibis,

00:58:24.000 --> 00:58:25.000
I think it's interesting

00:58:25.000 --> 00:58:27.000
that a lot of these

00:58:27.000 --> 00:58:29.000
data frame libraries,

00:58:29.000 --> 00:58:31.000
they try to base their API

00:58:31.000 --> 00:58:33.000
to be Pandas-like

00:58:33.000 --> 00:58:35.000
but not identical, potentially,

00:58:35.000 --> 00:58:36.000
you know, thinking of Dask

00:58:36.000 --> 00:58:38.000
and others.

00:58:38.000 --> 00:58:40.000
But this Ibis

00:58:40.000 --> 00:58:43.000
sort of has the ability

00:58:43.000 --> 00:58:45.000
to configure it and extend it

00:58:45.000 --> 00:58:46.000
and make it different,

00:58:47.000 --> 00:58:49.000
kind of like, for example, Dask,

00:58:49.000 --> 00:58:50.000
which is one of the backends here.

00:58:50.000 --> 00:58:51.000
Yeah.

00:58:51.000 --> 00:58:53.000
It does, but the API doesn't change, right?

00:58:53.000 --> 00:58:56.000
It just talks to the different backends.

00:58:56.000 --> 00:58:58.000
Yeah, there's different schools

00:58:58.000 --> 00:58:59.000
of thought on this.

00:58:59.000 --> 00:59:01.000
So there's another project

00:59:01.000 --> 00:59:02.000
called Modin,

00:59:02.000 --> 00:59:03.000
which is similar to Ibis

00:59:03.000 --> 00:59:04.000
in many ways

00:59:04.000 --> 00:59:05.000
in the sense of, like,

00:59:05.000 --> 00:59:07.000
transpilation and sort of dynamically

00:59:07.000 --> 00:59:08.000
supporting different backends

00:59:08.000 --> 00:59:11.000
but sought to closely emulate

00:59:11.000 --> 00:59:14.000
the, you know, exact details

00:59:14.000 --> 00:59:15.000
of, like, you know,

00:59:15.000 --> 00:59:17.000
the API call,

00:59:17.000 --> 00:59:18.000
the function name,

00:59:18.000 --> 00:59:19.000
our function arguments

00:59:19.000 --> 00:59:21.000
must be exactly the same

00:59:21.000 --> 00:59:22.000
as Pandas with the goal

00:59:22.000 --> 00:59:24.000
of being a drop-in replacement

00:59:24.000 --> 00:59:27.000
for people's Pandas code.

00:59:27.000 --> 00:59:28.000
And that's one approach,

00:59:28.000 --> 00:59:30.000
kind of the Pandas emulation route.

00:59:30.000 --> 00:59:33.000
And there's a library called Koalas

00:59:33.000 --> 00:59:34.000
for Spark,

00:59:34.000 --> 00:59:36.000
which is like a PySpark

00:59:36.000 --> 00:59:38.000
emulation layer for the Pandas API.

00:59:38.000 --> 00:59:39.000
And then there's other projects

00:59:39.000 --> 00:59:41.000
like Polars and Ibis

00:59:41.000 --> 00:59:43.000
and Dask DataFrame

00:59:43.000 --> 00:59:45.000
that take, like,

00:59:45.000 --> 00:59:46.000
design cues from Pandas

00:59:46.000 --> 00:59:48.000
in the sense of, like,

00:59:48.000 --> 00:59:49.000
the general way

00:59:49.000 --> 00:59:50.000
in which the API works

00:59:50.000 --> 00:59:52.000
but has made meaningful departures

00:59:52.000 --> 00:59:55.000
in the interest of doing things better

00:59:55.000 --> 00:59:58.000
in many ways than Pandas did

00:59:58.000 --> 01:00:01.000
in certain parts of the API

01:00:01.000 --> 01:00:02.000
and making things simpler

01:00:02.000 --> 01:00:04.000
and not being beholden,

01:00:04.000 --> 01:00:05.000
like, beholden to decisions

01:00:05.000 --> 01:00:06.000
that were made in Pandas,

01:00:06.000 --> 01:00:08.000
you know, 15 years ago.

01:00:08.000 --> 01:00:09.000
Not to say there's anything bad

01:00:09.000 --> 01:00:10.000
about the Pandas API,

01:00:10.000 --> 01:00:12.000
but, like, with any API,

01:00:12.000 --> 01:00:13.000
it's large.

01:00:13.000 --> 01:00:15.000
Like, it's very large,

01:00:15.000 --> 01:00:16.000
as evidenced by, you know,

01:00:16.000 --> 01:00:19.000
the 2,000 pages of documentation.

01:00:19.000 --> 01:00:22.000
And so I understand the desire

01:00:22.000 --> 01:00:23.000
to make things simpler

01:00:23.000 --> 01:00:25.000
while also refining certain things,

01:00:25.000 --> 01:00:27.000
making certain types of workloads

01:00:27.000 --> 01:00:29.000
easier to express.

01:00:29.000 --> 01:00:30.000
And so Polars, for example,

01:00:30.000 --> 01:00:33.000
is very expression-based.

01:00:33.000 --> 01:00:35.000
And so everything is column expressions

01:00:35.000 --> 01:00:36.000
and is lazy

01:00:36.000 --> 01:00:38.000
and not eagerly computed,

01:00:38.000 --> 01:00:41.000
whereas Pandas is eager execution

01:00:41.000 --> 01:00:42.000
just like NumPy is,

01:00:42.000 --> 01:00:44.000
which is how Pandas, you know,

01:00:44.000 --> 01:00:46.000
became eagerly executed

01:00:46.000 --> 01:00:48.000
in the first place.

01:00:48.000 --> 01:00:51.000
And so I think the mantra with Polars

01:00:51.000 --> 01:00:53.000
was we don't want to support

01:00:53.000 --> 01:00:55.000
the eager execution by default

01:00:55.000 --> 01:00:57.000
that Pandas provides.

01:00:57.000 --> 01:00:58.000
We want to be able to build expressions

01:00:58.000 --> 01:01:01.000
so that we can do query optimization

01:01:01.000 --> 01:01:02.000
and take inefficient code

01:01:02.000 --> 01:01:04.000
and under the hood rewrite it

01:01:04.000 --> 01:01:06.000
to, you know, be more efficient,

01:01:06.000 --> 01:01:07.000
which is, you know,

01:01:07.000 --> 01:01:10.000
what you can do with a query optimizer.

01:01:10.000 --> 01:01:11.000
So ultimately, like,

01:01:11.000 --> 01:01:12.000
and that matters a lot

01:01:12.000 --> 01:01:14.000
when you're executing code remotely

01:01:14.000 --> 01:01:17.000
or in, like, a big data system,

01:01:17.000 --> 01:01:19.000
that you want to have the freedom

01:01:19.000 --> 01:01:20.000
to be able to take, like,

01:01:20.000 --> 01:01:22.000
a lazy, you know, analytic expression

01:01:22.000 --> 01:01:25.000
and rewrite it, you know, based on.

01:01:25.000 --> 01:01:26.000
It might be like you need to

01:01:26.000 --> 01:01:28.000
seriously rewrite the expression

01:01:28.000 --> 01:01:30.000
in the case of, like, Dask, for example.

01:01:30.000 --> 01:01:33.000
Like, Dask has to do

01:01:33.000 --> 01:01:36.000
planning across a distributed cluster.

01:01:36.000 --> 01:01:37.000
And so, you know,

01:01:37.000 --> 01:01:39.000
Dask DataFrame is very Pandas-like,

01:01:39.000 --> 01:01:40.000
but it also includes

01:01:40.000 --> 01:01:42.000
some explicit details

01:01:42.000 --> 01:01:43.000
of being able to control

01:01:43.000 --> 01:01:44.000
how the data is partitioned

01:01:44.000 --> 01:01:46.000
and being able to have some knobs

01:01:46.000 --> 01:01:48.000
to turn in terms of, like,

01:01:48.000 --> 01:01:49.000
having more control

01:01:49.000 --> 01:01:50.000
over what's happening

01:01:50.000 --> 01:01:52.000
on a distributed cluster.

01:01:52.000 --> 01:01:53.000
And I think the goal there

01:01:53.000 --> 01:01:54.000
is, like, to give the developer

01:01:54.000 --> 01:01:55.000
more control as opposed to, like,

01:01:55.000 --> 01:01:57.000
trying to be intelligent, you know,

01:01:57.000 --> 01:01:58.000
make all of the decisions

01:01:58.000 --> 01:02:00.000
on behalf of the developer.

01:02:00.000 --> 01:02:02.000
So if you, you know,

01:02:02.000 --> 01:02:04.000
if you know about how, you know,

01:02:04.000 --> 01:02:05.000
know a lot about your data set,

01:02:05.000 --> 01:02:06.000
then you can make more,

01:02:06.000 --> 01:02:08.000
you can make, you know,

01:02:08.000 --> 01:02:10.000
decisions about how to schedule

01:02:10.000 --> 01:02:11.000
and execute it.

01:02:11.000 --> 01:02:13.000
Of course, Dask is building,

01:02:13.000 --> 01:02:14.000
you know, query optimization

01:02:14.000 --> 01:02:16.000
to start making more of those decisions

01:02:16.000 --> 01:02:17.000
on behalf of the user.

01:02:17.000 --> 01:02:20.000
But, you know, Dask has become

01:02:20.000 --> 01:02:22.000
very popular and impactful

01:02:22.000 --> 01:02:23.000
in making distributed computing

01:02:23.000 --> 01:02:25.000
easier in Python.

01:02:25.000 --> 01:02:26.000
So they've gotten, you know,

01:02:26.000 --> 01:02:28.000
I think gotten a long way

01:02:28.000 --> 01:02:29.000
without turning into a database.

01:02:29.000 --> 01:02:31.000
And I think Dask never aspired

01:02:31.000 --> 01:02:33.000
to be a database engine,

01:02:33.000 --> 01:02:35.000
which is a lot of distributed computing

01:02:35.000 --> 01:02:37.000
is, you know, not database-like.

01:02:37.000 --> 01:02:38.000
It could be distributed array computing

01:02:38.000 --> 01:02:40.000
or distributed model training

01:02:40.000 --> 01:02:42.000
and just being able to easily run

01:02:42.000 --> 01:02:43.000
distributed, you know,

01:02:43.000 --> 01:02:46.000
Python functions on a cluster

01:02:46.000 --> 01:02:48.000
and do distributed computing that way.

01:02:48.000 --> 01:02:49.000
It was amazing, like,

01:02:49.000 --> 01:02:51.000
how many people were using

01:02:51.000 --> 01:02:52.000
PySpark in the early days

01:02:52.000 --> 01:02:54.000
just for the convenience

01:02:54.000 --> 01:02:57.000
of being able to run Python functions

01:02:57.000 --> 01:03:00.000
in parallel on a cluster.

01:03:00.000 --> 01:03:01.000
Yeah, and that's pretty interesting

01:03:01.000 --> 01:03:04.000
and not exactly what it's designed for.

01:03:04.000 --> 01:03:05.000
Right.

01:03:05.000 --> 01:03:06.000
With Dask, you know,

01:03:06.000 --> 01:03:07.000
you probably come across situations

01:03:07.000 --> 01:03:10.000
where you do a sequence of operations.

01:03:10.000 --> 01:03:12.000
They're kind of commutative

01:03:12.000 --> 01:03:13.000
in the end in practice,

01:03:13.000 --> 01:03:15.000
but from a computational perspective,

01:03:15.000 --> 01:03:16.000
like, how do I distribute this

01:03:16.000 --> 01:03:17.000
amongst different servers?

01:03:17.000 --> 01:03:20.000
Maybe one order matters

01:03:20.000 --> 01:03:21.000
a lot more than the other

01:03:21.000 --> 01:03:23.000
out of performance, you know?

01:03:23.000 --> 01:03:24.000
Yeah.

01:03:24.000 --> 01:03:25.000
Yeah.

01:03:25.000 --> 01:03:26.000
Interesting.

01:03:26.000 --> 01:03:27.000
All right.

01:03:27.000 --> 01:03:28.000
One final thing.

01:03:28.000 --> 01:03:30.000
SQLGLOT?

01:03:30.000 --> 01:03:31.000
Yeah.

01:03:31.000 --> 01:03:34.000
So, SQLGLOT project started

01:03:34.000 --> 01:03:36.000
by Toby Mao.

01:03:36.000 --> 01:03:39.000
So, he's a Netflix alum

01:03:39.000 --> 01:03:41.000
and, you know,

01:03:41.000 --> 01:03:43.000
really talented developer

01:03:43.000 --> 01:03:45.000
who's created this SQL query

01:03:45.000 --> 01:03:48.000
transpilation framework library

01:03:48.000 --> 01:03:50.000
for Python and, you know,

01:03:50.000 --> 01:03:53.000
kind of underlying core library.

01:03:53.000 --> 01:03:54.000
And so, the problem

01:03:54.000 --> 01:03:55.000
that's being solved there

01:03:55.000 --> 01:03:57.000
is that SQL, despite being

01:03:57.000 --> 01:03:58.000
a quote-unquote standard,

01:03:58.000 --> 01:04:00.000
is not at all standardized

01:04:00.000 --> 01:04:03.000
across different database systems.

01:04:03.000 --> 01:04:04.000
And so, if you want to take

01:04:04.000 --> 01:04:06.000
your SQL queries written

01:04:06.000 --> 01:04:07.000
for one engine

01:04:07.000 --> 01:04:09.000
and use them someplace else,

01:04:09.000 --> 01:04:11.000
without something like SQLGLOT,

01:04:11.000 --> 01:04:12.000
you would have to manually rewrite

01:04:12.000 --> 01:04:15.000
and make sure you get the typecasting

01:04:15.000 --> 01:04:18.000
and coalescing rules correct.

01:04:18.000 --> 01:04:21.000
And so, SQLGLOT understands

01:04:21.000 --> 01:04:23.000
the intricacies and the quirks

01:04:23.000 --> 01:04:24.000
of every database dialect,

01:04:24.000 --> 01:04:26.000
SQL dialect,

01:04:26.000 --> 01:04:29.000
and knows how to correctly translate

01:04:29.000 --> 01:04:31.000
from one dialect to another.

01:04:31.000 --> 01:04:34.000
And so, IBIS now uses SQLGLOT

01:04:34.000 --> 01:04:35.000
as its underlying engine

01:04:35.000 --> 01:04:38.000
for query transpilation

01:04:38.000 --> 01:04:42.000
and generating SQL outputs.

01:04:42.000 --> 01:04:45.000
So, originally, IBIS had its own

01:04:45.000 --> 01:04:48.000
kind of bad version of SQLGLOT,

01:04:48.000 --> 01:04:50.000
kind of a query transpilation,

01:04:50.000 --> 01:04:53.000
like SQL transpilation

01:04:53.000 --> 01:04:55.000
that was powered by, I think,

01:04:55.000 --> 01:04:57.000
powered by SQLAlchemy

01:04:57.000 --> 01:04:59.000
and a bunch of custom code.

01:04:59.000 --> 01:05:00.000
And so, I think they've been able

01:05:00.000 --> 01:05:02.000
to delete a lot in IBIS

01:05:02.000 --> 01:05:04.000
by moving to SQLGLOT.

01:05:04.000 --> 01:05:05.000
And I know that, you know,

01:05:05.000 --> 01:05:07.000
SQLGLOT is also being used

01:05:07.000 --> 01:05:10.000
to power kind of a new,

01:05:10.000 --> 01:05:12.000
yeah, being used in people

01:05:12.000 --> 01:05:13.000
building new products

01:05:13.000 --> 01:05:15.000
that are Python-powered,

01:05:15.000 --> 01:05:16.000
things like that.

01:05:16.000 --> 01:05:18.000
So, and Toby, like,

01:05:18.000 --> 01:05:21.000
his company, Tobiko Data,

01:05:21.000 --> 01:05:22.000
they're building a product

01:05:22.000 --> 01:05:24.000
called SQL Mesh

01:05:24.000 --> 01:05:26.000
that's powered by SQLGLOT.

01:05:26.000 --> 01:05:28.000
So, very cool project

01:05:28.000 --> 01:05:29.000
and maybe a bit in the weeds,

01:05:29.000 --> 01:05:30.000
but if you've ever needed

01:05:30.000 --> 01:05:31.000
to convert a SQL query

01:05:31.000 --> 01:05:32.000
from one dialect to another,

01:05:32.000 --> 01:05:34.000
it's, yeah, SQLGLOT is here

01:05:34.000 --> 01:05:36.000
to save the day.

01:05:36.000 --> 01:05:37.000
I would say, you know,

01:05:37.000 --> 01:05:38.000
even simple things

01:05:38.000 --> 01:05:39.000
is how do you specify

01:05:39.000 --> 01:05:42.000
a parameter variable,

01:05:42.000 --> 01:05:44.000
you know, for a parameterized query,

01:05:44.000 --> 01:05:45.000
right?

01:05:45.000 --> 01:05:46.000
And Microsoft SQL Server,

01:05:46.000 --> 01:05:50.000
it's like at the parameter name

01:05:50.000 --> 01:05:52.000
and Oracle, it's like question mark

01:05:52.000 --> 01:05:53.000
or SQLite, I think it's also,

01:05:53.000 --> 01:05:54.000
you know, just that,

01:05:54.000 --> 01:05:55.000
even those simple things.

01:05:55.000 --> 01:05:56.000
It's a pain.

01:05:56.000 --> 01:05:57.000
Yeah.

01:05:57.000 --> 01:05:58.000
And without it,

01:05:58.000 --> 01:05:59.000
you end up with little bobby tables,

01:05:59.000 --> 01:06:00.000
which is also not good, so.

01:06:00.000 --> 01:06:01.000
That's true.

01:06:01.000 --> 01:06:02.000
That's true.

01:06:02.000 --> 01:06:04.000
Nobody wants to talk to him.

01:06:04.000 --> 01:06:05.000
Yeah, this is really cool.

01:06:05.000 --> 01:06:07.000
SQLGLOT, like polyglot,

01:06:07.000 --> 01:06:11.000
but all the languages of SQL.

01:06:11.000 --> 01:06:12.000
Nice.

01:06:12.000 --> 01:06:14.000
And you do things like,

01:06:14.000 --> 01:06:15.000
